// ── DATA ──
const currMods = [
  { slug: "public-speaking", title: "The Art of Public Speaking", months: "", tagline: "Presence. Persuasion. Authority.", summary: "A rigorous, progressive discipline in persuasion, presence, and executive communication — from voice, posture, and composure to rhetorical strategy, audience psychology, and the architecture of influence.", why: "This is not casual presentation practice. It is the discipline of learning how to stand before others, think clearly, speak with clarity, conviction, and control, and make an idea impossible to ignore.", body: "Every serious path in leadership begins with the ability to stand before others and speak with clarity, composure, and conviction. This discipline is not about presentation tricks or eliminating filler words. It is a progressive training in persuasion, presence, and executive communication.\n\nStudents begin with the fundamentals: voice, posture, breath, eye contact, structure, and composure under pressure. From there, the work advances into narrative design, rhetorical strategy, audience psychology, and the ability to hold attention without volume, theatrics, or force.\n\nGrounded in Aristotle's three modes of persuasion — ethos, pathos, and logos — students learn not only what to say, but when, how, and why to say it. By the end of the program, public speaking is no longer performance. It becomes authority made visible.", whatYouLearnLabel: "What Excalibur Students Will Learn", whatYouLearn: ["Voice mechanics — projection, pacing, tone variation, and the power of silence", "Physical presence — posture, eye contact, and gesture that conveys authority rather than anxiety", "Aristotle's three modes of persuasion: ethos, pathos, and logos", "Narrative architecture — how to build tension, deliver clarity, and leave one clear, memorable idea", "The five-minute pitch — developed, rehearsed, delivered to progressively demanding audiences", "Impromptu speaking — responding to unexpected questions without losing composure", "Advanced rhetoric - parallel structure, contrast, repetition, and the rule of three", "The psychology of audience management — reading a room and recovering from mistakes in real time", "Executive communication — briefing a team, presenting recommendations, speaking to faculty, professionals, and invited evaluators, and communicating with authority in professional settings", "Debate and Q&A defense — defending ideas under pressure with clarity, confidence, and discipline"], outcomes: ["Deliver structured, compelling speeches and pitches to live audiences with composure", "Defend ideas under pressure and respond to difficult or hostile questions without losing their thread", "Develop stronger vocal control, posture, eye contact, and executive presence", "Have their presentations recorded, reviewed, and coached through multiple live speaking exercises"], quote: "“The human voice is the most powerful instrument in the world. The tragedy is that most people never learn to play it.” — Benjamin Disraeli" },
  { slug: "financial-literacy", title: "Financial Literacy & Business Acumen", months: "", tagline: "Understand capital. Think like an owner.", summary: "Financial literacy is one of the most useful forms of fluency a young person can develop, yet it is rarely taught with seriousness or practical application. This module teaches the fundamentals of business from an ownership perspective: how companies generate revenue, protect margins, price products, manage costs, and decide what is worth pursuing.", why: "Our students learn to read a business the way founders, executives, and investors do — not as a set of abstract numbers, but as a living system of decisions, trade-offs, incentives, opportunities, trade-offs, and consequences.", body: "Financial literacy is one of the few skills every student will use for the rest of their life. Yet while traditional education teaches mathematics, history, and science, few students ever learn how money works, how businesses create value, or how founders, executives, and families make financial decisions.\n\nFinancial Literacy & Business Acumen introduces students to the principles that govern money, markets, entrepreneurship, and value creation. This module teaches the fundamentals of business from an ownership perspective: how companies generate revenue, protect margins, price products, manage costs, and decide what is worth pursuing.\n\nOur students learn to read a business the way founders, executives, and investors do — not as a set of abstract numbers, but as a living system of decisions, trade-offs, incentives, opportunities, trade-offs, and consequences.\n\nFinancial literacy is not about being naturally good with numbers. It is about learning to see reality clearly.", whatYouLearn: ["Revenue, gross margin, and profit — and why the differences matter", "How to read a profit-and-loss statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement", "Unit economics — customer acquisition cost, lifetime value, contribution margin", "Pricing strategy — cost-plus, value-based, competitive, and dynamic pricing", "Compound interest and the mathematics of long-term wealth building", "Equity structures — how ownership in a company is divided, diluted, and valued", "How investors evaluate businesses — multiples, EBITDA, comparable transactions", "Live financial analysis of local business partneres, presented to guest practitioners"], outcomes: ["Can read and interpret a basic P&L statement with confidence", "Can explain the unit economics of any business they encounter", "Has presented a financial analysis of a real business to a professional audience"], quote: "Financial literacy is not about being naturally good with numbers. It is about learning to see reality clearly." },
  { slug: "capital-markets", title: "Capital Markets, Investing & Wealth Management", months: "", tagline: "Capital. Risk. Markets. Wealth.", summary: "Most people are affected by financial markets for their entire lives without ever being taught how they actually work. This module builds genuine market literacy from the ground up — covering how equity markets are structured, how companies are valued, how crypto works as both a financial and technological phenomenon, and why the discipline of serious investors begins with judgment, not intuition.", why: "Earning money is only the beginning. The ability to grow it, protect it, allocate it, and understand risk is what separates short-term income from long-term financial strength.\n\nStudents who understand investing gain a deeper view of business, markets, incentives, ownership, and wealth creation. They learn to think beyond consumption and begin seeing money as a tool for opportunity, diversification, independence, and portfolio growth.", body: "This module builds market literacy from the ground up. Students learn how equity markets are structured, how companies are valued, how earnings, growth expectations, interest rates, news, and investor psychology influence price movement, and why markets often react before the wider public understands why.\n\nCrypto is studied as both a financial and technological phenomenon. Students examine blockchain, digital assets and emerging financial technologies, decentralized finance, and the distinction between real innovation and speculation.\n\nThe module introduces the habits of serious investors and traders: thesis development, risk management, psychology of loss aversion and emotional control. Through simulated market exercises and paper trading, students learn how quickly emotion can distort judgment — and why discipline matters.\n\nThe goal is to develop students who understand how capital moves, how markets think, and how financial decisions should be approached with judgment and restraint, when money, emotion, and uncertainty collide.", whatYouLearn: ["How equity markets work — exchanges, market makers, order types, and price discovery", "How to analyze a public company — valuation ratios, earnings, revenue multiples, and what they actually tell you", "Market behavior and chart interpretation — trend lines, support and resistance, volume signals", "Crypto fundamentals — blockchain mechanics, tokenomics, DeFi, and how to evaluate a project", "Risk management — position sizing, stop losses, portfolio construction, and the mathematics of risk and permanent loss", "The psychology of trading — loss aversion, confirmation bias, overconfidence, and how professionals override them", "Macroeconomic forces — how interest rates, inflation, Fed policy, and global events move markets", "Simulated portfolio exercise — building and defending an investment thesis before faculty and guest evaluators", "Venture capital, private equity, and startup investing", "Investment simulations and portfolio-building exercises", "How investors evaluate companies and opportunities"], outcomes: ["Can interpret basic market data, valuation signals, and chart patterns", "Understands the difference between investing and speculation — and the disciplines each requires", "Has completed a live paper trading simulation and presented their portfolio thesis to a professional panel", "Understands the mechanics of public and private capital markets", "Can analyze investment opportunities using fundamental frameworks", "Can evaluate risk, return, and portfolio-construction principles"], quote: "The market is a device for transferring money from the impatient to the patient. — Warren Buffett" },
  { slug: "ai-technology", title: "AI, Technology & Innovation", months: "", tagline: "Direct the tools reshaping every industry.", summary: "AI is not a separate subject at Excalibur. It is a working instrument used across business research, financial modeling, competitive analysis, pitch development, and venture strategy.", why: "The most important question in business today is not whether AI will affect your industry — it will. The question is whether students will understand these tools well enough to direct them with judgment, verification, and purpose.\n\nStudents who understand how AI actually works — and how to deploy it with judgment — will operate at a level of speed, precision, and analytical capacity that gives them a lasting advantage.", body: "At Excalibur, artificial intelligence is not treated as a standalone subject — it is a working instrument used across business research, financial modeling, competitive analysis, pitch development, and venture strategy. From the first week onward, AI is integrated across disciplines, used the way entrepreneurs, executives, and strategists use it: to find patterns, test assumptions, compare markets, improve decisions, and work with greater speed, clarity, and verification.\n\nStudents learn to deploy AI for rapid market research, real-time competitive analysis, and on-demand financial modeling — tasks that once required teams of analysts and weeks of work. They are trained not merely to use tools, but to ask better questions of them.\n\nThis module examines how the most consequential AI systems work beneath the surface — the training data, parameters, and inference processes that determine what they can and cannot do. Students learn when to trust AI output, when to verify it, and when to override it entirely.\n\nThe ethical dimensions of AI — bias, intellectual property, job displacement, and builder responsibility — are studied not as abstract concerns but as real decisions that founders, executives, and engineers face today.\n\nThe future will not belong to passive users of technology. It will belong to those with the judgment to direct it.", whatYouLearn: ["How large language models actually work — training data, parameters, inference, and limitations", "AI as a business tool — market research, competitive analysis, financial modeling", "Prompt engineering — how to instruct AI to produce reliable, high-quality outputs", "No-code platform development — building functional tools and automations without code", "AI in each industry sector — how technology is disrupting every major field", "Critical evaluation of AI output — when to trust it, when to verify, when to override", "The ethics of AI — bias, IP, job displacement, and builder responsibility", "Building an AI-powered business concept from research through pitch", "Workflow automation — using AI to eliminate repetitive tasks and accelerate decision-making", "Competitive intelligence and market analysis using AI tools", "AI in venture development — research, validation, modeling, and pitch preparation", "How to evaluate AI startups and technology investments as a business analyst"], outcomes: ["Uses AI tools for research and strategy as a natural workflow, not a novelty", "Has built at least one functional no-code tool or automation", "Can articulate how AI works beneath the interface to someone unfamiliar with it", "Has completed an AI-powered competitive analysis of a real industry", "Understands the ethical and economic implications of AI on business and careers", "Can evaluate an AI startup or product with informed analytical judgment"], quote: "The future will not belong to passive users of technology. It will belong to those with the judgment to direct it." },
  { slug: "art-of-selling", title: "The Art of Selling & Marketing", months: "", tagline: "Persuasion with integrity. Influence with discipline.", summary: "From brand strategy and customer acquisition to capital raising and executive negotiation, business depends on the ability to communicate value clearly. This module treats it as a core life skill — training students in applied persuasion as it actually happens: unscripted, high-stakes, and consequential.", why: "The ability to communicate value is one of the most important skills in business and life.\n\nWhether presenting a venture, applying for university, interviewing for a position, leading a team, raising capital, or building a company, success often depends on the ability to persuade others and earn their confidence.\n\nStudents who understand sales and marketing develop stronger communication skills, greater commercial awareness, and a deeper understanding of human decision-making.", body: "No matter how brilliant an idea, product, service, or venture may be, it has little value if nobody knows it exists.\n\nSales and marketing sit at the center of every successful business. From brand strategy and customer acquisition to capital raising and executive negotiation, business depends on the ability to communicate value clearly. This module treats it as a core life skill — training students in applied persuasion as it actually happens: unscripted, high-stakes, and consequential.\n\nThis module introduces students to the principles of persuasion, positioning, branding, customer acquisition, and commercial communication. Students learn why people buy, how decisions are made, how trust is established, and how successful organizations communicate value in language that moves people to act.\n\nAt Excalibur, students learn the real mechanics of persuasion: listening, questioning, positioning, objection handling, confidence under pressure, and the ability to explain why something matters. This is not about tricks or pressure. It is about clarity, trust, timing, and the courage to make a case.\n\nThe best salespeople are rarely the loudest voices in the room. They are disciplined listeners who ask better questions, diagnose more carefully, and earn trust before they ask for action.\n\nMarketing is the discipline of making something worth finding. Students study brand strategy, audience psychology, positioning, digital channels, content, and the architecture of campaigns that actually move people.", whatYouLearn: ["Consultative selling — asking, listening, diagnosing, and proposing with precision", "Customer psychology — why people buy, hesitate, trust, and decide", "Branding, positioning, and differentiation", "Sales conversations — opening, discovery, presentation, objection handling, and closing", "Cold outreach, warm introductions, referrals, and follow-up strategy", "Marketing channels, customer acquisition, and growth campaigns", "Messaging, offers, copywriting, and persuasive communication", "Focus groups, market research, customer needs, and pain-point analysis", "Paid advertising basics — audiences, budgets, platforms, and performance metrics", "Live role-play, recorded feedback, and campaign presentations before faculty and coaches"], outcomes: ["Develop and present a complete marketing campaign for a real or simulated venture", "Understand customer psychology, buying behavior, and the principles of persuasion", "Build customer personas and conduct focus groups, surveys, and market research", "Conduct a complete consultative sales conversation with genuine listening", "Handle objections without defensiveness or pressure", "Articulate the ethical framework separating trusted advisors from manipulators"], quote: "\u201cThe aim of marketing is to know and understand the customer so well the product or service fits him and sells itself.\u201d — Peter Drucker" },
  { slug: "leadership", title: "Leadership, Influence & Decision-Making", months: "", tagline: "Lead through judgment, trust, and earned authority.", summary: "Leadership is tested most clearly under pressure: in moments of pressure, uncertainty, disagreement, and responsibility. This module teaches the disciplines behind effective leadership — building trust, reading people, managing conflict, making decisions without perfect information, communicating clearly, and staying composed when others are looking for direction.", why: "Leadership is not a personality type. It is a set of disciplines — practiced under pressure, refined through failure, and expressed most clearly in moments of uncertainty.\n\nStudents who develop genuine leadership capability — not just confidence, but judgment, composure, and the ability to move people — carry an advantage that no technical skill can replicate.", body: "Leadership is tested most clearly under pressure: in moments of pressure, uncertainty, disagreement, and responsibility.\n\nThis module teaches the disciplines behind effective leadership — building trust, reading people, managing conflict, making decisions without perfect information, communicating clearly, and staying composed when others are looking for direction.\n\nStudents examine the difference between power and influence, explore emotional intelligence, conflict resolution, mental fortitude, team dynamics, and the invisible work of preparation that separates genuine leaders from those who merely hold titles.\n\nThrough simulations, case studies, leadership challenges, and real-time team exercises, students develop not just the vocabulary of leadership — but the actual habits and instincts it requires.\n\nA title can be given. Authority has to be earned.", whatYouLearn: ["The five forms of power — legitimate, reward, coercive, expert, referent — and which create lasting authority", "Emotional intelligence — self-awareness, self-regulation, empathy, motivation, and social skill", "Decision-making under uncertainty — frameworks for consequential choices with incomplete information", "Conflict resolution — how to navigate disagreement and maintain relationships across rupture", "Team dynamics — stages of team development and roles within high-performing teams", "The invisible work of leadership — preparation, follow-through, and trust-building habits", "Crisis communication — how to lead when things are going wrong and everyone is watching", "Crisis leadership simulation — a live exercise guiding a fictional organization through a real-time emergency", "Mental fortitude — staying composed, focused, and decisive under pressure", "Giving and receiving feedback — building cultures of accountability and high performance", "The ethics of leadership — how the best leaders build trust without sacrificing results", "Personal leadership framework — identifying strengths, blind spots, and practices for growth"], outcomes: ["Can identify the five forms of power and explain which create lasting influence", "Has led a team through a live crisis simulation", "Can articulate a personal leadership framework as a set of practices, not a personality description", "Demonstrates composure and clear communication under simulated high-pressure conditions", "Has developed and presented a leadership case study on a historical or contemporary figure", "Understands the relationship between emotional intelligence and effective team leadership", "Has completed a structured self-assessment of leadership strengths and development areas"], quote: "“Leadership is the art of getting someone else to do something because he wants to do it.” — Dwight D. Eisenhower" },
  { slug: "business-models", title: "Business Model Analysis", months: "", tagline: "Break down any business. Understand the market. Find the logic.", summary: "This discipline trains students to look beneath the surface of a company and understand the structure underneath: how it creates value, earns revenue, controls costs, reaches customers, defends margins, and survives competition. Students learn to analyze businesses the way founders, executives, and investors do — not by asking whether an idea sounds impressive, but by asking whether the model works.", why: "Every organization operates within a competitive environment. Whether launching a venture, leading a team, entering a profession, or building a career, business model literacy is one of the most powerful analytical skills a young person can develop.\n\nA student who can quickly explain how a company creates value, earns revenue, and defends its position has an analytical advantage most students are never trained to develop.", body: "Students learn to break down any company — from a neighborhood café to a global technology firm — and explain, with clarity and precision, how it generates revenue, where costs concentrate, what advantage protects it, and what single vulnerability could weaken or collapse the model. They learn to ask the questions that actually matter: What drives demand? What scales? What breaks under pressure? What protects the margin? What could cause the model to fail? The result is not theory — but fluency.\n\nThis module introduces students to the fundamental principles of business strategy and model design. Students graduate able to analyze, challenge, and understand a wide range of businesses and industries. Every successful company, from Apple and Nike to Airbnb and Ferrari, operates according to a business model. Behind every product, service, and customer experience is a set of deliberate choices about how value is created, delivered, and captured.\n\nStudents study the eight core business models — subscription, marketplace, direct-to-consumer, advertising, franchise, freemium, professional services, and hardware-plus-consumable — and learn how each one determines margins, scalability, and competitive position.\n\nThe course goes beyond identification. Students learn how to evaluate a model's strengths and vulnerabilities, how incumbents defend their positions, and how disruption actually happens — not as a sudden collapse, but as a slow erosion that management often refuses to see.\n\nCase studies include Netflix, Apple, Amazon, Airbnb, and Costco — businesses that have redefined their categories through model innovation, not just product excellence.\n\nThe module culminates in a live deconstruction exercise: students analyze local business partneres, present their findings in Investor Briefing format, and defend their assessments before faculty and guest professionals.", whatYouLearn: ["The eight business models: subscription, marketplace, DTC, advertising, franchise, freemium, professional services, hardware-plus-consumable", "How to identify a company's core value proposition and revenue capture mechanism", "Competitive advantage analysis — cost leadership, differentiation, focus, network effects", "Vulnerability mapping — identifying the greatest strategic risk in any business model", "Investor Briefing format — how analysts present company analysis to investment committees", "Case studies: Netflix, Apple, Amazon, Airbnb, Costco — iconic business model evolution", "Business model disruption — how it happens and why incumbents fail to respond", "Live deconstruction of local businesses: model, strengths, blind spots"], outcomes: ["Identifies the business model of any company within minutes of exposure", "Delivers a five-minute Investor Briefing on a real public company to a professional audience", "Completes four quarterly business model analyzes, progressively more sophisticated", "Understands how successful organizations are structured and operate", "Can analyze industries, competitors, and business opportunities", "Can identify competitive advantage and strategic positioning", "Develop stronger critical thinking and problem-solving abilities", "Can apply strategic frameworks to ventures, projects, and applied challenges"], quote: "A brilliant product in the wrong business model is just an expensive lesson." },
  { slug: "intellectual-depth", title: "Intellectual Depth & The Art of Class", months: "", tagline: "Think deeply. Move with ease among ideas and people.", summary: "Technical skill can open doors. Intellectual range and social intelligence determine what happens inside the room. This discipline develops the qualities that make a young person not only capable, but memorable: cultural literacy, conversation, etiquette, taste, listening, judgment, and the ability to engage intelligently across history, philosophy, psychology, business, politics, and the arts. Students learn to engage serious ideas with clarity and confidence.", why: "These are not decorative skills. They are the foundation of presence — the kind that makes others trust, remember, and respect the person in front of them.", body: "Influence is rarely earned through technical skill alone. In professional settings — boardrooms, interviews, dinners, galleries, meetings, and negotiations — people are assessed for judgment, class, manners, intellectual range, and the way they carry themselves. This discipline exists to ensure Excalibur students are not only capable, but distinguished.\n\nStudents are formed to converse with ease across philosophy, history, psychology, and the arts — part of the shared language of serious education and leadership. They engage with the foundations of classical liberal education: Homer on honor and leadership; Plato and Aristotle on virtue, reason, and rhetoric; Seneca and Marcus Aurelius on self-command and duty; Machiavelli on power, perception, and statecraft.\n\nThis is not academic display. It is social fluency: the ability to ask thoughtful questions, listen well, read a room, connect ideas, and carry oneself with quiet authority. The goal is not performance. It is presence - the kind that builds trust and remains long after the conversation ends.: thoughtful questions, cultural awareness, composed manners, and the ability to connect ideas effortlessly. This is the quiet authority that comes from preparation, manners, judgment, and intellectual range — the kind that helps students build trust, ask better questions, and leave a thoughtful impression.", whatYouLearn: ["Stoic philosophy as a practical framework — Marcus Aurelius, Seneca, Epictetus applied to modern business", "The art of patronage — what the Medici teach about investing in human potential and building influence", "Literary analysis for leaders — The Great Gatsby, The Alchemist examined through ambition and meaning", "Historical leadership case studies — Lincoln, Churchill, Mandela, Jobs", "The social arts — formal dining protocol, professional conversation, how to work a room without working it", "How to be remembered — substance, specificity, and genuine curiosity about others", "Writing with precision — expressing a complex idea in one clear, specific sentence", "The intellectual habits of the most accomplished people — how they read, think, and synthesize"], outcomes: ["Can draw on classical philosophy, history, and literature naturally in professional conversations", "Navigates a formal dinner or professional networking event with ease", "Has developed a personal reading practice and can discuss ideas from at least five significant books"], quote: "The mind is not a vessel to be filled, but a fire to be kindled. — Plutarch" },
  { slug: "college-admissions", title: "College Admissions & Personal Development", months: "", tagline: "Start forging your own path. Dig Deeper. Ignite your true passions.", summary: "This module helps students prepare not only for college applications, but for the deeper question behind them: who they are becoming, what they care about, and where their energy naturally comes alive.", why: "College applications reveal preparation, direction, and seriousness. The student who has spent time understanding their own direction, building real things, and developing a genuine point of view will always present more compellingly than the student who has only assembled a transcript. Excalibur exists to build that student.", body: "This module helps students prepare not only for college applications, but for the deeper question behind them: who they are becoming, what they care about, and where their energy naturally comes alive.\n\nStudents work with Excalibur’s college advisor on application strategy, personal narrative, portfolio presentation, recommendation preparation, interview readiness, and how their Excalibur experience can strengthen their college applications and future academic goals.\n\nEach student participates in monthly 1:1 personal development sessions designed to help them reflect seriously on their strengths, interests, ambitions, values, and sense of direction. The goal is not to force a life plan too early, but to help each student understand what creates curiosity, discipline, and spark — and how to begin building around it.", whatYouLearn: ["How to identify and articulate your intellectual interests and personal values", "College application strategy — positioning, school selection, timeline, and narrative arc", "How to write a compelling personal statement rooted in genuine experience", "How to present your Excalibur portfolio and applied work in applications", "Interview preparation — composure, storytelling, and how to handle hard questions", "How to approach recommendation letters — who to ask, how to guide them, what to include", "Personal reflection practice — strengths, interests, patterns, and direction", "How to build a personal roadmap that extends beyond the application season"], outcomes: ["Leaves with a clear college application strategy and timeline", "Has written a personal statement draft reviewed by the Excalibur college advisor", "Has participated in at least four 1:1 personal development sessions and documented key findings about their own direction"], quote: "The strongest essays usually come from students who understand not only what they have done, but who they are becoming." },
  { slug: "negotiation-psychology", title: "Negotiation & Human Psychology", months: "", tagline: "Understand people. Command outcomes.", summary: "Every consequential outcome in business and life involves persuading, influencing, or negotiating with another person. This module develops the psychological intelligence and practical skills students need to navigate high-stakes conversations with clarity, confidence, and integrity.", why: "The most important conversations in life — interviews, partnerships, conflicts, sales conversations, leadership moments, and future capital raises — are negotiations. Students who understand human psychology and the mechanics of negotiation enter every consequential conversation with an advantage that most adults never develop.\n\nThe focus is understanding people. Students learn how trust is built, why relationships matter, and how strong personal and professional networks create opportunities throughout life.", body: "Every consequential outcome in business and life involves persuading, influencing, or negotiating with another person.\n\nThis module develops the psychological intelligence and practical skills students need to navigate high-stakes conversations with clarity, confidence, and integrity. Students study how people think, decide, and respond — the cognitive biases, emotional triggers, and social dynamics that shape every negotiation.\n\nThey learn the mechanics of preparation: knowing your position, understanding the other party's interests, setting anchors, making concessions strategically, and knowing when to walk away.\n\nThrough live simulations — salary negotiations, business deals, partnership discussions, and conflict resolution scenarios — students develop the ability to stay composed, think clearly, and reach outcomes that work.\n\nThe module also covers the psychology of influence and persuasion: Cialdini's principles, the mechanics of trust-building, and the ethical boundaries that separate skilled negotiation from manipulation.\n\nBy the end, students have not just learned about negotiation. They have practiced it — under pressure, with feedback, and against real resistance.", whatYouLearn: ["The psychology of decision-making — how people actually make choices under uncertainty", "Cognitive biases that affect negotiation — anchoring, loss aversion, reciprocity, and more", "Interest-based negotiation — separating positions from underlying needs", "Preparation frameworks — BATNA, ZOPA, anchor-setting, and concession strategy", "Active listening and reading non-verbal signals in high-stakes conversations", "Influence principles — Cialdini's six drivers of human behavior", "Trust-building — how credibility and rapport are established and maintained", "Conflict resolution — navigating disagreement without damaging relationships", "Live negotiation simulations with structured feedback and coaching", "Ethics of persuasion — where skilled influence ends and manipulation begins", "Networking and relationship-building as a long-term strategic asset", "High-stakes conversation management — interviews, team conflicts, partnership conversations, sales discussions, and future deal terms"], outcomes: ["Has completed multiple live negotiation simulations with structured coaching and feedback", "Can prepare a full negotiation strategy including anchor, BATNA, and concession plan", "Understands the psychological principles that drive human decision-making and behavior", "Can identify and counteract cognitive biases in real-time negotiation situations", "Demonstrates composed, strategic communication in high-pressure conversation scenarios", "Understands the ethical boundaries of persuasion and can articulate them clearly", "Has practiced professional relationship-building, follow-up, and networking strategy"], quote: "\u201cLet us never negotiate out of fear. But let us never fear to negotiate.\u201d — John F. Kennedy" },
  { slug: "industry-sectors", title: "Industry Sectors Rotation", months: "One new sector each month", tagline: "Understand industries. Enter serious rooms prepared.", summary: "Each month features a dedicated guest speaker from a different industry, a sector-specific case study, and an analytical exercise. Over ten months, students explore twelve major sectors of modern commerce.", why: "Most people leave education with some familiarity with one or two sectors and limited working knowledge of many others. An Excalibur graduate who can speak with informed intelligence across twelve industries develops unique social, intellectual, and professional range.", body: "Each month features a dedicated guest speaker from a different industry, a sector-specific case study, and an analytical exercise. Over ten months, students explore technology, finance, real estate, food and hospitality, e-commerce, healthcare, media, automotive and sports, manufacturing, energy and sustainability, and luxury brands. By the end of the rotation, students develop a Sector Journal documenting their analyzes across major industries.", whatYouLearn: ["Technology & AI — platform economics, software margins, how software companies scale and defend margins", "Finance & Venture Capital — equity, debt, cap tables, term sheets, how investors decide", "Real Estate — development economics, cap rates, wealth-building mechanics", "Food & Hospitality — unit economics, brand-building in a commoditized market", "E-Commerce & Retail — customer acquisition, lifetime value, supply chains, DTC brands", "Healthcare & Biotech — FDA pathways, healthcare economics, why it requires unusual patience", "Media & Entertainment — attention economics, the creator economy, IP valuation", "Legal & Professional Services — contracts, IP, equity agreements every entrepreneur needs to understand", "Manufacturing & Supply Chain — how physical things are made, moved, and sold at scale", "Energy & Sustainability — renewable economics, carbon markets, major entrepreneurial opportunities ahead", "Automotive & Sports — automotive business models, motorsport economics, franchise valuation, athlete branding", "Luxury & Premium Brands — psychology of desire, scarcity, heritage, and premium pricing"], outcomes: ["Holds a Sector Journal with twelve completed industry analyzes", "Can speak knowledgeably about any of the twelve sectors to a professional in that field", "Has engaged with guest speakers and leaders across the sector rotation"], quote: "The more industries the student understands, the more they realize how similar the underlying principles are — and how different the specifics are. Both things matter." },
  { slug: "legal-foundations", title: "Legal Foundations for Founders", months: "Foundation Semester", tagline: "Understand what you are signing before you sign it.", summary: "Most founders learn the legal realities of business the hard way — after the damage is done. This module delivers the foundational legal knowledge every entrepreneur needs before they launch, raise capital, hire a partner, or sign a contract: entity structure, equity mechanics, intellectual property, and the term-sheet clauses that determine how ownership, control, and outcomes may change.", why: "The law does not reward ignorance. Founders who don't understand entity structure, equity dilution, or intellectual property often discover the consequences years later — during a fundraise, a partnership dispute, or an acquisition that reveals what they unknowingly gave away.\n\nThis module does not make students lawyers. It makes them clients who know exactly what they're reading, what questions to ask, and when to walk away.", body: "Entity types, equity structures, intellectual property, founder agreements, NDAs, and term sheet mechanics. The knowledge most founders learn the hard way — delivered before it matters.\n\nThis module is taught by a practicing attorney with direct startup experience: someone who has sat across the table from founders, investors, and acquirers and seen what goes wrong when the legal foundation is built on assumptions rather than clarity.\n\nStudents learn how to choose the right entity, structure co-founder equity with appropriate protections, protect their intellectual property before its value is obvious, and evaluate the terms investors propose without the fog of inexperience.\n\nThe module also examines real cases — partnership disputes, IP theft, dilution surprises, and acquisition terms that shocked founders who hadn't read what they signed. These are not cautionary abstractions. They are patterns that repeat, and can be avoided.\n\nBy the end, students understand the legal architecture of a business — not as a speciality to be delegated, but as a foundation every founder must be able to read.", whatYouLearn: ["Business entity types — LLC, C-corp, S-corp: what each means, how each is taxed, and when to choose one over another", "Equity structure — vesting schedules, cliff periods, co-founder departure scenarios, and anti-dilution provisions", "Intellectual property — trademarks, copyrights, patents, and trade secrets: what protects what, and when to file", "Contracts and NDAs — what makes them binding, what makes them dangerous, and what most people miss", "Founder agreements — what a properly structured agreement protects and what a missing clause has cost real founders", "Term sheet mechanics — the five clauses every founder must understand before accepting a term sheet", "Cap table basics — how a company's ownership evolves from founding through Series A and beyond", "Due diligence — what acquirers and investors look for, and how founders are caught unprepared", "Real case studies — partnership disputes, IP disputes, and acquisition surprises that changed outcomes"], outcomes: ["Can select the appropriate entity structure for a given business and explain the reasoning", "Understands equity vesting, cliff periods, and how co-founder departures affect cap tables", "Can identify the key provisions in a term sheet and explain what each one means for founders", "Knows the difference between trademark, copyright, patent, and trade secret — and which applies when", "Has reviewed a sample founder agreement and identified its key protections and gaps", "Understands what an NDA does and does not protect, and when one is appropriate"], quote: "The best time to understand the legal foundation of a business is before the first serious decision is made." },
  { slug: "personal-finance", title: "Personal Finance & Wealth Building", months: "Foundation Semester", tagline: "Earning money is only the beginning.", summary: "Many young people begin earning before they understand saving, investing, taxes, credit, and long-term financial planning. This module builds a complete personal financial framework — from budgeting and tax literacy to compound growth, retirement vehicles, and how families, founders, and advisors structure and protect long-term capital.", why: "Financial independence is not a salary. It is a set of habits, decisions, and structures built over time — the earlier, the more powerful.\n\nStudents who understand money at seventeen make better decisions at twenty-five, thirty, and fifty. The mathematics of compound growth are not abstract: early, disciplined investing can change the mathematics of a young person's financial future. This module makes those numbers visible and personal.", body: "Budgeting, tax fundamentals, compound interest, retirement vehicles, real estate as a wealth vehicle, and how financially accomplished families structure and protect capital.\n\nThis module closes a gap that almost no formal education addresses. Schools teach algebra and history. They do not teach students how to file a tax return, open a brokerage account, evaluate a lease versus a purchase, or understand why early, disciplined investing can change the mathematics of a young person's financial future.\n\nThe module is taught in partnership between the Academy Dean — a former Managing Director and financial professional with thirty years of high-level experience — and an outside specialist in personal financial planning or wealth management.\n\nStudents apply every concept to themselves: building a real personal budget, running compound growth calculations with their own hypothetical savings, and reviewing real investment vehicles available to them today.\n\nThe goal is not financial theory. It is financial fluency — the ability to make informed, confident decisions about money for the rest of their lives.", whatYouLearn: ["Budgeting and cash management — building a real personal budget that works", "Tax fundamentals — how income tax works, how founders and self-employed individuals are taxed differently, and how to read a W-2 and 1099", "Compound interest — applied to a sixteen-year-old with real numbers and real timelines", "Retirement accounts — Roth IRA, traditional IRA, and 401(k) basics — how each works, how each is taxed, and why starting now changes the math permanently", "Brokerage accounts — how to open one, how index funds work, and how to build a simple, durable investment portfolio", "Real estate as a personal wealth vehicle — how appreciation, leverage, and rental income create long-term wealth", "Credit — how credit scores work, what damages them, and how to build a strong credit history early", "The difference between assets and liabilities — and why most people get it backwards", "How financially accomplished families structure capital — trusts, estate planning basics, and generational wealth transfer", "Insurance fundamentals — what coverage is designed to protect, where costs can become excessive, and what young adults often misunderstand"], outcomes: ["Has built a complete personal monthly budget using their own projected income", "Can explain compound interest and demonstrate its long-term impact with real calculations", "Understands the difference between a Roth IRA, 401(k), and taxable brokerage account — and understands which account types may be appropriate to discuss with a parent or financial advisor", "Can read a basic tax return and explain what each section represents", "Has written a one-page personal financial plan covering saving rate, investment vehicle, and a ten-year projection", "Understands how real estate works as a wealth vehicle and can explain the basic mechanics of leverage"], quote: "" },
  { slug: "pr-crisis", title: "Public Relations & Crisis Communication", months: "Foundation Semester", tagline: "Reputation is built quietly. It can be lost overnight.", summary: "Every organization — and every person — will face a moment when the story being told about them is not the one they would choose. This module teaches the principles of earned media, reputation management, and crisis communication: how to understand, prepare, and respond before a narrative is set by others, and how to respond when things go wrong.", why: "Reputation is one of the most valuable and least understood assets in business and life. Founders who understand public relations build trust before they need it. Those who don't discover its importance during a crisis — when every hour of delayed response amplifies the damage.\n\nThe same principles that govern corporate crisis communication apply to a student's personal brand, digital presence, and the way they are perceived by universities, employers, and future partners.", body: "Earned media, crisis communication frameworks, the first twenty-four hours, and the specific difference between a response that contains a crisis and one that amplifies it.\n\nThis module is taught by an outside specialist — a working PR professional or senior communications executive with direct experience managing earned media, public narratives, and real crises for organizations and individuals.\n\nStudents study the mechanics of how public narratives form: how journalists think, how stories spread, and how organizations either shape their own story or lose that ability to someone else. The distinction between earned, paid, and owned media is examined in depth — each serves a different purpose, and many early founders confuse them.\n\nThe crisis communication section is built around real case studies: Johnson & Johnson's Tylenol response in 1982, United Airlines' catastrophic handling of the Dao incident in 2017, Airbnb's pivot during COVID-19, and WeWork's implosion under public scrutiny. Each case reveals the same truth: how you respond in the first twenty-four hours determines whether a crisis is contained or expanded.\n\nStudents complete a mock media interview under live faculty pressure — prepared, pressured, recorded, and reviewed.", whatYouLearn: ["Earned vs. paid vs. owned media — how each serves a different purpose and why founders confuse them", "How journalists and media outlets evaluate stories — what makes something newsworthy, and what makes a pitch ignored", "Media relations fundamentals — how to reach journalists, build relationships, and earn coverage", "Crisis communication frameworks — the principles that determine whether a response contains or amplifies a problem", "The first 24 hours — why initial response timing and framing determine outcomes", "Message discipline — how to stay on message under adversarial questioning", "Spokesperson training — who should speak, what they should say, and what they should never say", "Digital reputation management — how social media accelerates crises and how organizations respond", "Case studies: Johnson & Johnson Tylenol (1982), United Airlines / Dr. Dao (2017), Airbnb / COVID-19, WeWork implosion", "Personal brand and digital presence — how students are perceived before they walk into a room", "Mock media interview — live, recorded, and reviewed with direct coaching"], outcomes: ["Can articulate the difference between earned, paid, and owned media and when to use each", "Has completed a mock media interview under pressure and received structured coaching feedback", "Can identify the crisis communication failure in each of the four case studies and explain what alternative responses might have changed the outcome", "Understands the mechanics of how a story spreads — and how early intervention shapes or loses narrative control", "Has audited their own digital presence and developed a personal reputation management plan", "Understands the first-24-hours principle and can apply it to a hypothetical crisis scenario"], quote: "It takes twenty years to build a reputation and five minutes to ruin it. If you think about that, you'll do things differently. — Warren Buffett" },
];

